ewhall, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Loxley, Staffordshire, England":"Loxley, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1437–":"1437–Deceased","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","1437–Male":"1437–Deceased","1438–1489":"1438–1489","1448–1491":"1448–1491","1468–1528":"1468–1528","1406–Male":"1406–Deceased","1411–Female":"1411–Deceased","1491":"1491","1437":"1437","1448":"1448","1468":"1468","ABT 1461":"about 1461","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1411":"1411","1430":"1430","about 1433":"about 1433","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Newhall, Derbyshire, England":"Newhall, Derbyshire, England","Newhall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newhall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Newhall, Derbyshire, England":"Newhall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Loxley, Staffordshire, England":"Loxley, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dethick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Dethick (Derbys)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":18,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":112,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Dethick was born in 1437, in Newhall, Derbyshire, England, his father, Thomas Dethick, was 31 and his mother, Elizabeth Kinardsley, was 27. He married Frances Ticknall about 1461, in Newhall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1437–":"1437–Surnud","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1438–1489":"1438–1489","1448–1491":"1448–1491","1468–1528":"1468–1528","1406–Male":"1406–Surnud","1411–Female":"1411–Surnud","1491":"1491","1437":"1437","1448":"1448","1468":"1468","ABT 1461":"umbes 1461","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1411":"1411","1430":"1430","about 1433":"umbes 1433","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Newhall, Derbyshire, England":"Newhall, Derbyshire, England","Newhall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newhall, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Newhall, Derbyshire, England":"Newhall, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom